messageBody:
I know that feeling.
I've several projects I'd like to attempt with QS on computers which I'm
holding off on until the proposal is accepted/rejected.

I have to say that I'm not especially in love with the original names,
but they are more widely known and they're also the ones listed in the
manual.
I don't see it as a big deal really, no one uses Unicode names in day to
day speech anyway, so you'll still be able to use whichever name you like.

I haven't submitted the proposal yet.
One of the requirements for the proposal is outline font with a suitable
license, I was going to ask if I could submit yours?
I was going to just clean up QS Block's kerning and submit that, but
yours looks nicer (IMO).

Paul Tremblay wrote:
>
> amd64_hacker wrote:
> >
> >
> > Have you had a chance to cast your eye over it yet?
> > I'd really like to get the proposal posted, its icon is starting to
> > glare at me.
> > We've had two or three eyes on it so I think this is more or less what
> > we want.
> > I'm still a bit worried that I may have made it too essay-like, what do
> > you think?
> >
>
> No one seems to have responded. I entered this group too late to really
> comment, thought I have looked over the archives. Getting our own
> unicode set would really help everyone--especially me right now, who is
> making a font.
>
> This is probably too late and probably not a suggestion you welcome, but
> I prefer the revised names (Bob instead of Bay, Zhivago instead of Jai,
> etc.) If we get Unicode approval, the rather inferior original names
> will become official.
>
> Thanks for all your work. Have you already submitted the proposal?
>
> Paul
>
>
